sql:
SELECT MAX(avg_final_grade) AS highest_avg_final_grade
FROM (
  SELECT course_id, AVG(final_grade) AS avg_final_grade
  FROM grades
  GROUP BY course_id
);

external_knowledge:
- "Recent" refers to the latest enrollment date for each course;
- "Majority" refers to the most common occurrence of a grade among students;
- "Highest recent final grade" is the top grade achieved by students in their most recent course enrollments.

- "Distinction" is a grade status given to students who score more than 80% in their exams;
- "Merit" is a grade status given to students who score more than 70% but less than or equal to 80% in their exams;
- "Pass" is a grade status given to students who score 70% or less in their exams.

- "Scholars" refers to students;
- "Embarked on the journey of learning" means they are enrolled in courses and have taken exams;
- "Pursuing" refers to the courses they are enrolled in;
- "Illuminated by the average grade" means the results are enhanced by including the average final grade for each course.

- "Crowded courses" refers to courses where the number of enrolled students is more than 80% of the course's total capacity;
- "Blossoms" metaphorically refers to students;
- "Academic garden" is a metaphor for the academic institution or the educational environment.
